    the simple office of love, but in all the accoutrement,
    complement, and ceremony of it.
Truly, I am so glad you have nobody here.
' that any madness I
    ever yet beheld seem'd but tameness, civility, and patience,
    to this his distemper he is in now.
I am glad the fat knight
    is not here.
But I am glad the knight is not
    here; now he shall see his own foolery.
I am undone: the knight is here.
How should I bestow
    him?
Shall I put him into the basket again?
No, I'll come no more i' th' basket.
May I not go
    out ere he come?
What shall I do?
I'll creep up into the chimney.
I'll go out then.
Alas the day, I know not!
Mistress Page and I will
    look some linen for your head.
I would my husband would meet him in this
    shape; he cannot abide the old woman of Brainford; he
